title: For Sale:  How to spot a SCAMMER!
postcontent:
Go to this post: http://www.armslist.com/posts/3646467/pennsylvania-rifles-for-sale--springfield-timberwolf-imi-pump-44-mag-penny-start

First, you should note what kind of seller they are. In this case they are a private seller.

Second, before inquiring about a firearm you should always search GunBroker for the exact same posting; see here:
http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=448468087

Boom red flag right away!

Third, the location of this post says PA, yet when I emailed him to inquire if he would ship to an out of state FFL he said he is in WA. This contradicts with the post. 

His exact initial response: 

"Yes i will definitely ship to your FFL dealer, Am in WA. Where are you located ?Price includes shipping to your FFL, do you have an FFL dealer that you work with? I'll be shipping as an individual to your FFL and i'll include a copy of my DL in it for his record and Transfer purpose. I will take USPS Money Order Or Bank To Bank Wire Transfer, and please send your FFL info."

Finally, this person English is piss pour

Watch out for scammers! There is a special place in hell for these bottom feeders. The last picture is of my response to him emailing me asking if I was still interested because he has other buyers lined up (sure you do buddy).

title: For Sale:  Common Sense
postcontent:
You know the saying, "If it sounds too good to be true, it probably is."

Lately (mainly the last couple of days), I have seen listings for things that look VERY suspicious.  For instance, DVDs showing you how to convert an AR-15 to full auto.  The listing claims that it's First Amendment protected to communicate this information; I'm not so sure.  I believe it is possible to be charged with conspiracy to even talk about converting a semi-auto to full-auto.  It is WITHOUT QUESTION a crime to do so.  Did you know it is a crime to be in possession of a single PART which would be used to make a machine gun?  You don't even have to use it.  Just owning it is a crime.

Now tonight I see an ad for an AK-47 style rifle that to my eye looks either like a short barreled rifle (controlled much like a machine gun) and/or equipped with a suppressor (aka silencer - also controlled much like a machine gun).

So I ask you fellow 'listers - Are you sure it's safe to do business with these kinds of people, who advertise things that could land your keister in jail?  

If you don't know the law, be SKEPTICAL.  Better than to end up with a criminal conviction (which, by the way, means you will lose ALL your guns - FOREVER).

Thanks for listening.  Send me a buck if you feel grateful (grin).

P.S.  I went back and looked at the listing that seemed to be a short-barreled rifle with a suppressor.  Looks like the suppressor is fake, but I don't see anything on the website of the manufacturer that lists the barrel length.  Probably legit, but my point is to WATCH OUT.  Don't give the I-594 crowd something to brag about.  Use your common sense.
